 points for spiritual commemoration and para-liturgical campaigns.This volume, grounded on extensive research into the original manuscripts, and presenting numerous new manuscript witnesses, argues that some of the letters are post hoc "inventions", composed by generations of scribe-readers who visited crusading sites from the twelfth century on, adding new layers of meaning in the form of interpolations and post-scripts. Drawing upon this new understanding, and blurring the distinction of epistolary "reality", it rewrites central aspects of the history of the First Crusade, considering the documents in a new way: as markers of enthusiasm and support for the crusade movement among monastic clergy, who copied and consumed them as a form of scribal crusading. Whether authentic letters or literary "confections", they functioned as communal sites for the celebration, commemoration and memorialisation of the expedition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCrusadesyFirst, 1096-1099xHistoriography. 0aCrusadesyFirst, 1096-1099xSources. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAlexios I.  aBattle of Ascalon.  aByzantine Empire.  aHeinrich Hagenmeyer.  aHistoria Ierosolimitana.  aOderisius I.  aPetchenegs.  aQuellenkritik.  aRobert I of Flanders.  aStephen of Blois.  aUrban II.1 aSmith, Thomas William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311143096640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781805432739?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781805432739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781805432739/original  a978-3-11-143096-6  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV